{
  "Election": {
    "election_id": "h93tm4",
    "title": "BV2171 — The Condorcet centrist, minimal form (8 voters) — squeezed out by first-choice methods, elected by the rest",
    "description": "The smallest electorate that still reproduces the whole center-squeeze symptom: 8 voters, three candidates — Avery (left pole), Blake (right pole), Casey (centrist). 3 rank Avery > Casey > Blake, 3 rank Blake > Casey > Avery, 1 ranks Casey > Avery > Blake, 1 ranks Casey > Blake > Avery. Casey is the Condorcet winner — beats Avery 5-3 and Blake 5-3 head-to-head — but has only 2 first-choice votes, the fewest. The same 8 voters are counted seven ways, every method BetterVoting supports. The whole-ballot methods — STAR, STAR-PR, Approval (approve your top two), and Ranked Robin (the Condorcet method) — elect Casey. The first-choice methods — RCV-IRV, STV, and Choose-One Plurality — eliminate Casey first and, because the electorate is perfectly symmetric between the two poles, deadlock Avery and Blake in an exact tie. This is the minimal companion to the full 100-voter version (BV2172), the profile from the 'Should we always elect the Condorcet winner?' explainer.",
